## What to Look For

As you navigate through the <em>Mocana API Reference</em>, you'll find %common elements:

- <b>Hyperlinks</b> &mdash;You'll quickly notice a plethora of hyperlinks in this API
Reference. Functions contain hyperlinks to their source files; descriptions
contain hyperlinks to related pages; pages contain hyperlinks to functions and
files; and so on. You can quickly find yourself unsure how you got to a display!
So don't forget the breadcrumb path, and of course your browser's Back button.

- <b>File lists</b> &mdash;Every directory has a page listing the files
that contain that product's externally-accessible API functions. To display the
file list, do either of the following:
 - From the navigation pane's \b Pages options, click <b>NNN Files</b> (where <b><em>NNN</em></b>
 is the name of the directory you're in, or "API Files" at the top level).
 - From the display pane's description section, click the appropriate hyperlink;
 its location varies depending on which directory you're in.

@image html ex_file_list.png "Viewing a Product's File List"

- <b>Function lists</b> &mdash;Every directory has one or more pages listing the
corresponding product's or component's externally-accessible API functions.
These lists are logical function groups, such as "EAP-FAST Functions" and
"EAP-RADIUS Functions", of the the alphabetical function list provided in the
navigation pane.

- <b>Descriptions</b> &mdash;Every page, structure, function, and so on has a description page.

- <b>Callback functions</b> &mdash;Callback functions do not appear directly in the
navigation pane. Instead, you access them through the structure in which their
function pointer is assigned. For example, the $%funcPtrLookupPSK$ callback
function description is accessible from the $%sslSettings$ structure
description.

<b>Tip</b> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Many of the directories have a page that lists the
applicable callback functions and provides direct hyperlinks. For example, the
%ssl directory has a page titled, "sslSettings Callbacks".

